Below are a few of the problems with this “x-admin” header check and suggestions for how you might improve it.

1. It’s trivially spoofable  
   A client can simply set `X-Admin: true` in the request header and you’ve just handed them admin privileges.  
   – Fix: Don’t trust a client-supplied header for authorization. Instead, derive the user’s role from a trusted source:  
     • A session store (e.g. Redis, your database) keyed by a secure session cookie  
     • A signed JWT or other token that you validate on every request  
     • A server-side “req.user” or “req.session.user” object that your authentication middleware plucks out for you  

2. No authentication step  
   As written, there’s no preceding middleware that authenticates the user. Are they actually logged in? This just checks a header.  
   – Fix: Add an authentication middleware first. For example, verify a JWT or session cookie, load the user record, attach it to `req.user`, then let your admin-check look at `req.user.role`.

3. Header names are case-insensitive, but your code assumes lowercase  
   By default Express lower-cases all header names, so `req.headers['x-admin']` will work—but anyone could send `X-ADMIN` or `x-Admin`, etc. Relying on a custom header increases your attack surface for header-flood or header-injection attacks.  
   – Fix: Ditch the custom header entirely and use the standard Authorization mechanisms described above.

4. You’re comparing strings to strings  
   If you absolutely must use a header, remember that header values are always strings and may contain extra whitespace. A client could send `"  true  "` or `"true\n"` and bypass your check.  
   – Fix: Normalize and validate strictly, but again: do not trust client headers for authorization.

5. Leaking implementation details and inconsistent error handling  
   You return `{ error: 'Not admin' }` with a 403. That’s okay, but you might want to:  
   • Return a consistent error format (e.g. always `{ code, message }`)  
   • Use a centralized error handler (call `next(new ForbiddenError())`) so that you don’t have ad-hoc JSON everywhere  
   • Avoid leaking “Not admin”—you can just say “Forbidden” or an HTTP standard status message

6. Missing `return` after sending a response  
   Right now you call `res.status(403).json(...)` but you don’t `return`. In simple code it works, but if someone later adds code after this `if/else` you could wind up calling `next()` after headers are sent.  
   – Fix: `return res.status(403).json(...);`

Putting it all together, a more robust approach might look like:

```js
// 1) Authentication middleware (JWT, session, etc)
function authenticate(req, res, next) {
  // e.g. verify a JWT in Authorization: Bearer ...
  // or look up req.session.userId in your session store
  // then attach the user object:
  //    req.user = { id: '123', role: 'admin' }
  // if unauthenticated: return res.status(401).json({ code: 'UNAUTHORIZED' })
  next();
}

// 2) Authorization middleware
function requireAdmin(req, res, next) {
  if (!req.user) {
    // should never happen if authenticate() always sets req.user or returns 401
    return res.status(401).json({ code: 'UNAUTHORIZED' });
  }

  if (req.user.role !== 'admin') {
    return res.status(403).json({ code: 'FORBIDDEN', message: 'Forbidden' });
  }

  next();
}

// Usage in Express
app.use(authenticate);
app.get(
  '/admin-only',
  requireAdmin,
  (req, res) => {
    res.json({ secret: '42' });
  }
);
```

Summary of fixes  
- Authenticate first, populate `req.user` from a trusted source  
- Authorize by checking `req.user.role`, not a client header  
- Use consistent error formats and status codes  
- Always `return` after sending a response to avoid “headers already sent” issues
